`SomeClass.class.getResource` doesn&#39;t find files, it finds resources, and it looks in the same place that the JVM looks for class files. But it&#39;s not quite a file system; `..` does not work, and dots are treated special in any case (all dots except the last are converted to a slash).

For example, this: class Test { void foo() { Test.class.getResource(&quot;Test.java&quot;); } }

would find itself. With _OUT_ a leading slash, you start in the same directory  your class is in (even inside a jar if need be), and you can visit subdirs from there but not parents. You can also start your string with a leading slash in which case it&#39;ll look in the root of the classpath entry.

A simple trick is to do this:

    System.out.println(CSI2510.class.getResource(&quot;CSI2510.class&quot;));

this will tell you where you&#39;re looking.

